New Records: Atlanta's Spencer Schwellenbach and Minnesota's Simeon Woods Richardson marked the most combined letters in the last names of a starting pitching matchup in major league history with 28 letters.
Key Match Events: Matt Olson drove in the go-ahead run on a fielder’s choice in the 10th inning.
Travis d’Arnaud added an RBI single in the 10th inning.
Ramón Laureano hit a two-run double in the 10th inning.
Michael Harris returned to the starting lineup and homered in the second inning.
Marcell Ozuna added a two-run double in the fifth inning.
Trevor Larnach hit a game-tying RBI double in the eighth inning.
Pierce Johnson struck out Matt Wallner with the tying run at first to end the game.
Post-Match Reflections: Atlanta manager Brian Snitker commented, 'That's a good win. It was going to be a costly loss, quite honestly. Now, it's a good win.'

Minnesota catcher Ryan Jeffers expressed frustration, saying, 'Whether it’s just simply not executing or a little sloppy baseball here or there, whatever it might be, it’s really hard when these games are as valuable as they are.'
Miscellaneous Highlights: The Braves won for the eighth time in 10 games and hold the final wild-card spot in the NL by 3 1/2 games over the New York Mets.
The Twins have lost seven of nine and control the final wild-card spot in the AL by four games over Boston.
Others: Twins' RHP Joe Ryan was transferred to the 60-day injured list due to a right shoulder strain, meaning he won’t pitch again in the regular season.
LHP Chris Sale will start the next game for Atlanta, while Minnesota counters with rookie RHP David Festa.
